{{History of China |BC=1}}
{{stack|{{contains Chinese text}}{{Chinese |c={{linktext|<U+4E09>|<U+7687>|<U+4E94>|<U+5E1D>}} |p=S<U+0101>nhu<U+00E1>ng W<U+01D4>d<U+00EC> |w=San Huang Wu Ti |wuu=Se Waon U Ti}}}}

The '''Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors''' were a group of [[Chinese mythology|mythological]] rulers and deities from ancient [[China]] during the period circa 2852 BC to 2070 BC, today considered [[culture heroes]].<ref name="clight2">{{cite book|title=China's Imperial Past: An Introduction to Chinese History and Culture|author=Hucker, Charles|publisher=[[Stanford University Press]]|year=1995|isbn=9780804723534|page=22}}</ref> According to received history, this period preceded the [[Xia Dynasty]].<ref name="Mor">Morton, W. Scott Morton.  Morton, William Scott.  Lewis Charlton M.  (2005). China: its history and culture. McGraw-Hill. ISBN 0-07-141279-4, ISBN 978-0-07-141279-7, p. 14.</ref>

In myth, the Three Sovereigns were demigods who used their abilities to help create mankind and impart to them essential skills and knowledge. The Five Emperors were exemplary sages possessed of great moral character.

== Variations ==

Depending on the source, there are many variations of who classifies as the Three Sovereigns or the Five Emperors.  There are six to seven known variations.<ref name="clight1"><U+5289><U+7152>/<U+8457>. (2002) Chinese civilization in a new light. Commercial press publishing.  ISBN 962-07-5314-3, p. 142.</ref>  Many of the sources listed below were written from much later dynasties.

The following appear in different groupings of the Three Sovereigns: [[Fuxi]] (<U+4F0F><U+7FB2>), [[N<U+00FC>wa]] (<U+5973><U+5AA7>), [[Shennong]] (<U+795E><U+8FB2>), [[Suiren]] (<U+71E7><U+4EBA>), [[Zhu Rong (god)|Zhurong]] (<U+795D><U+878D>), [[Gong Gong]] (<U+5171><U+5DE5>), [[Heavenly Sovereign]] (<U+5929><U+7687>), [[Earthly Sovereign]] (<U+5730><U+7687>), [[Human Sovereign|Tai Sovereign]] (<U+6CF0><U+7687>), [[Human Sovereign]] (<U+4EBA><U+7687>),  and even the [[Yellow Emperor]] (<U+9EC4><U+5E1D>).

The following appear in different groupings of the Five Emperors:  [[Yellow Emperor]] (<U+9EC3><U+5E1D>), [[Zhuanxu]] (<U+9853><U+980A>), [[Emperor Ku]] (<U+56B3>), [[Emperor Yao]] (<U+582F>), [[Shun (Chinese leader)|Shun]] (<U+821C>), [[Shaohao]] (<U+5C11><U+660A>), Taihao (<U+592A><U+660A>), and [[Yan Emperor]] (<U+708E><U+5E1D>).

There are study believes that ancient Egyptian come to China around 1000BC and founded Zhou dynasty, declaring themselves as the descendant of Xia dynasty, which is also the same title of what the ancient Egyptian declare them to be in their Hieroglyphic. According to Mu Tianzi Legend<U+300A><U+7A46><U+5929><U+5B50><U+4F20><U+300B>a Mu Tianzi<U+7A46><U+5929><U+5B50>of Zhou took 5 years and paid a visit to Egypt to memorise the ancestor and he met a female Pharaoh or princess there. 

===Three Sovereigns===
The Three Sovereigns, sometimes known as the Three August Ones, were said to be [[god-kings]] or [[demigods]] who used their magical powers to improve the lives of their people. Because of their lofty virtue, they lived to a great age and ruled over a period of great peace.  The Three Sovereigns are ascribed various identities in different [[History of China|Chinese historical]] texts.  The [[Yellow Emperor]] is supposedly the ancestor of the [[Huaxia]] people.<ref name= "history1"><U+738B><U+6046><U+5049>. (2005) (2006) <U+4E2D><U+570B><U+6B77><U+53F2><U+8B1B><U+5802> #1 <U+9060><U+53E4><U+81F3><U+6625><U+79CB>. <U+4E2D><U+83EF><U+66F8><U+5C40>. ISBN 962-8885-24-3, p. 13.</ref> The [[Mausoleum of the Yellow Emperor]] was established in [[Shaanxi Province]] to commemorate the ancestry legend.<ref name="history1" />

